item.description:

The battlefields of the grim-dark future are scattered will the everyday materiel of the industrial and military complex required to process war on a galactic scale.

This set offers a sample of a cargo crate, cargo hauler, blank trailer, and pallet of materiel.

These could be printed at 200% for 15mm gaming terrain, or, if you are ambitious, 400% for 28-32mm scale gaming. The models are sufficiently detailed to be printed at larger scale, yet simple and robust enough to print at their intended 6-8mm scale.

This set contains 4 STLs; a sample of the full set, available here:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/epic-cargo-road-train-scatter-terrain-6mm-8mm-scale

The full set allows you to customise your selection. It can be used to create cargo 'road trains', linking multiple trailers and cargo containers to create thematic barriers for your miniatures to take cover behind, or individual pieces to add character to the bases of larger miniatures.

They would also make suitable 'toys' what could be added to 28-32mm scale models, adding a layer of horror and inhumanity to the devastation surrounding your grim-dark characters.

The crane and defence trailer is compatible with my other Epic tank turrets, so can be replaced with any of the turrets in this collection:
https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/8mm-scale-grim-dark-tank-turrets-of-russ-nedius

Please see my other designs for other wargaming STLS.

I am an amateur enthusiast 3D designer, and appreciate all support and constructive feedback. Please check out my other designs for more wargame models, and please consider following me, post a make, and enjoy my models. If you would like to support my work, please leave a comment, like the design, or make a donation via my profile! Thanks!

The battlefields of the grim-dark future are scattered will the everyday materiel of the industrial and military complex required to process war on a galactic scale.

This set offers a range of cargo containers, goods transport, trucks, tugs, trailers, cranes and crates to add a little more character to your battlefields and bases.

These could be printed at 200% for 15mm gaming terrain, or, if you are ambitious, 400% for 28-32mm scale gaming. The models are sufficiently detailed to be printed at larger scale, yet simple and robust enough to print at their intended 6-8mm scale.

This set contains 46 STLs, allowing you to customise your selection. It can be used to create cargo 'road trains', linking multiple trailers and cargo containers to create thematic barriers for your miniatures to take cover behind, or individual pieces to add character to the bases of larger miniatures.

They would also make suitable 'toys' what could be added to 28-32mm scale models, adding a layer of horror and inhumanity to the devastation surrounding your grim-dark characters.

The crane is compatible with my other Epic tank turrets, so can be replaced with any of the turrets in this collection:

Idol of an evil deity from beyond time and space. Perfect as a dungeon-dressing for [Passage to Yondoor](https://www.illgottengames.net/shop/p/passagetoyondoor-coreset), but originally designed for my new board game, [Apocalopolis](https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/illgottengames/apocalopolis). This piece makes for a fun alternative to the asteroid that comes with the base game. There's an STL lever that will work with the game's launcher included here for anyone getting Apocalopolis, but for everyone else, enjoy an FDM support-free bit of scatter terrain.

Bring the charm of early 20th-century America to your tabletop with this beautifully crafted Small Town STL Set, designed by InfinitePrint 3D and now available under official license on Proxywars.

Inspired by real architecture from 1900s small-town America, this set captures the essence of a bygone era, from corner barbershops and bakeries to classic brick facades and streetlamp-lined sidewalks. Whether you're staging a noir-style narrative, building a diorama, or expanding your wargaming terrain, these models are a perfect fit for historical, pulp, or modern alternate history settings.

This looks _suspiciously_ like my [Modular Utility Building](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6838588), don't you think? 
OK, yeah, I fancied having one that was full height - that is, the same height as a GW Sector Fronteris hab block, and therefore also the same height as a [Fronteris style bunker](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6988922). It is, very approximately, 60x60x70mm.
For my own use I thought I'd go all in on the vents; make it some sort of cooling tower type thing, with a simple style vaguely influenced by some belfry louvres. I've kept in some more basic walls too, if that's more your style (or you plan to embellish them yourself).

### Compatibility

Style-wise, it obviously takes heavy cues from the Sector Fronteris hab units.

The pipe ports are the standard size expected on GW's 40k terrain - 25.6mm diameter.

The side pipe ports have a centre-line height of 14.5mm, which matches other terrain, e.g. Thermic Plasma Conduits.. Their outer face is 30.5mm from the centre point, so if you have two opposite each other they'll be 61mm apart, which should be a familiar size to those used to e.g. Sector Mechanicus components.

The roof is the same height as that of a Sector Fronteris hab unit, and the roof with a port should match the ports on those hab units too.

### Assembly

You will need:
* 4x *pillars*
* 4x *walls*
* 1x *roof*
If you chose walls with *ports*, you'll also need
* 1+ *pipe ends*

Walls push into pillars from behind. I recommend putting the roof in unglued as you put together the rest, then gluing it in last.

Pillars can be mirrored for a bit more variety.

### Pre-supports

The supported files here are the way I did them for myself, successfully. Is it the best? No. The walls and pillars are definitely over-supported, but I wasn't going to go back and change something that worked.

As you may see from the pictures, I did _not_ print non-louvred walls. The supports have been applied in the same way, but I have not actually printed these specifically.

### FAQ

* What's with the extra holes on the pipe ports in the photos but not on the STLs?
 _I have bizarre hopes of putting a lot of magnets everywhere. I'm not doing this in a way that I think makes sense to most people, so I didn't think it was worth sharing those. You can have the clean ones that actually look good by themselves!_

This is a set for creating a city building as a terrain for any wargame in 1/285 (6mm) scale. The set allows you to assemble both an intact (undamaged) buildings and a destroyed ones (ruins). You can assemble a building of any height you want by printing the required number of intermediate floors.


There is one option with square windows (marked with number 1) and the second with rounded windows (marked with number 2).


To make it easier to paint the windows, I made it a separate piece that can be painted in advance (for example, with spray paint) and inserted inside the walls.


I also made a set of interior parts in case you don't use windows or want to make glass from transparent material.

Do It Yourself (DIY) terrain scenery for WH40k. This "Knight's Gate" is 150mm X 202mm / 5.9" X 7.95" (Width and Height). It can be affixed on a wall and closed, or you can use both sides to create a gate that opens.

The inspiration for these doors has been some old GW art and a commission that required the incorporation of imperial Knight Titan themes.

A "sibling door" can be found in my other posts under:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5669332

Other DIY pieces and greebles can be found here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/vontragg/collections/42607514/things

I have used a number of shields that I found all over the place. If I have failed to give attribution, please contact me and I will be happy to correct any omissions.

A complete collection of retro-themed Gothic Ruins for table top gaming. These are the full set of 20 ruins that make up the full set of the sample set released earlier, available here: https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/retro-gothic-corner-ruins-set-1

Included in this set are 20 corner ruins, the floor piece for the raised platform on the two tallest corner ruins, plus two floor templates in case anyone wants to break them up a bit for some floor details on the ground level.

Inspired by the cardboard terrain I used in my youth, these turn those 2D flat terrain pieces into fully 3D models, to look more fitting on a modern gaming table!

Scaled to suit 28mm-32mm models, I actually designed them to be printed out at 50% scale for 15mm gaming. They even work well all the way down to 25% scale for 8mm gaming!

Perfect for reliving past wargaming experiences, or for giving your current games a bit of a Retro theme!

Please check out my other wargaming models including the first part of this set, and if you like this set, please consider liking the file, following me, or even making a donation! Let's face it: Even in the far future, people are still obsessed with efficiency, doing more with less. So it is with maintaining the Imperious Leader's far-flung dominion, and the most efficient method of moving stuff is still the train. And when you have enemies, those trains make sweet, juicy targets, necessitating adding arms and armor to repel the bad guys.

This set includes not only nine different train cars, but compatible track segments. The various train cars have round guide lugs on the underside that serve to keep the cars centered on the tracks.

The GothiTech Armored Train includes:

- Armed Locomotive
- Flatbed Car
- Boxcar
- Tanker Car
- Passenger Car
- Nuclear Fuel Car
- Artillery Car (cannon prints separately and can be mounted up for firing or down for travel)
- Troop Car (includes mounting points for two turrets)
- Air Defense Car (includes two antiaircraft missile turrets)
- Five Track Segments (Straight Single, Curved Single, Y-Split, Straight Double, and Curved Double)

Here's my set of modular building elements that allows you to build gothic-like structures for your wargaming terrain. I designed it for FDM printers.

The initial idea was to be able to create simple gothic-like walls in both undamaged and damaged form, so this is the reason why there are no floor tiles just yet.

There are no fancy connecting mechanism - use the glue, Luke! I prefer to use quick-drying basing glue.

**1.0v - Initial Release**

- Includes 27 wall and column modules.

**Updates**

- 18-07-2023: after some more printing, I can confirm that resizing the modules down to 80% still works great. I can also confirm that the modules print easily on a resin printer - with no supports, placed directly on the build plate. To save resin, you can hollow the columns (don't forget to add the drainage holes).

Loads of containers and container handling goodness! Stationary container cranes, walking container cranes, quad container haulers, container skates, container land trains, and more! A variety of container stacks! A confusing plethora of files! These containers and handling equipment make a great container yard terrain setup, or just lots of small vehicles and scatter terrain to give your battlefields some life.

Models include:
The big stationary container crane is presented in several models, with the container 'rack' in different positions. A seperate part is included for a container hanging from cables.

Quad mech 'walking' container cranes in several models. They can also use the hanging container part if you print the version with no rack. (Its another quad industrial mech!)

The container Train is a multi-part model of a tractor and one or more trailers to make up a 'train' that is meant to service the stationary cranes. Empty trailers are included along with those loaded with one or two containers.

Container Stackers are trucks with piston lifts that allow them to drive over single containers, or lift high enough to double-stack. Handy for moving containers but can't stack as high as the big walking cranes.

Container skates are a variation of the mech skates (see the mech repair posting!) either loaded or unloaded; they're an alternative to the trains for moving containers and look best when being loaded/unloaded by the walking cranes.

Container stacks in different configurations and heights, along with a few single containers.

A Buildermech with a container flatbed is also included (See my Buildermech posting for lots of other options - the crane version would also be handy in a container yard. Also, see my modular ships to have something the big cranes can offload!

Modeled in 6mm scale.

**Go to the "Thing Files" tab to individually download the files - Thingiverse is giving an odd 404 error when trying to use the "Download all files" buttons**

The perfect restaurant for watching S7 broadcasts or kicking back with the local mercs for a beer. This building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support placing units on top in all hexes for playability. The top of version B has additional supports for two edge hexes for extra stability. It is 1 level tall in most areas, except for the front two hexes where it is 1.5 levels tall, if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are eight files. For each of version A and B, one has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. Using the NoText versions, you can paint custom names on the front, print off logos to attach, or leave it blank.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

Notable features:
-An in-universe themed restaurant name.
-Fantastic custom logo and details to give it a proper BBQ joint look.
-Detailed design including doors, windows, and a detailed roof with greebles.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

It's a big quad industrial mech! The Drillermech is a BIG mech (for 6mm anyway), intended to operate as an all terrain mobile drilling platform, able to sink a well just about anywhere you might need it to go. 

The model is a little bit elaborate. The default parts are divided to make printing less of a headache. The original .3mf file is included in case you feel the need to split it up further. (Microsoft 3D builder is a decent part splitter and is free).

This mech is modeled from real drilling platforms, with pipe handling arms, a rather large top drive, iron roughneck, and so forth. The big cylinder in the back is the pipe rack, intended to be reloaded from the back or just swapped for another full cylinder. Just remember - don't shoot the active drilling rig, you have no idea what it's sitting on!

Also included is a 'waterline' model for those rigs deployed in shallow water areas.

A classy Chinese restaurant to add to your city, this building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support placing units on top in all hexes for playability. It is 1 level tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are four files. One has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. Using the NoText versions, you can paint custom names on the front, print off logos to attach, or leave it blank.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

**Notable features:**
-Detailed design including doors, windows, and a detailed roof with greebles.
-Asian-inspired font used for the store name.
-Large yin-yang logo made and placed on the front of the restaurant.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

In the 31st century, this originally Canadian business has rebranded to be even more popular! This building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support placing units on top for playability. It is 2 levels tall on the higher levels and 1 level tall on the lower levels if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

This is a two part print. Part 1 of the building can be used standalone as any large commercial building if you print the version without text and a logo. Part 2 is an automotive center add-on that can be placed on either side of the main building to make it larger, as seen in the photos above.

There are six files. Two have the building sections on hexes, two are hexless so that you can print the ones that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions of Part 1 that have the text removed from the front of the building. Using the NoText versions, you can populate your tabletop with custom commercial/big-box stores by painting names on the front or printing off logos to attach.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

Notable features:
-Based off of a very popular Canadian business, using a similar font and building design style.
-Detailed design including large front windows, two main entrances, garage doors, windows, and bollards to protect the building from bad drivers.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

A radome designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. These provide great scatter terrain to add detail to your military bases. It also looks great in an open field as extra cover. The top of the B version is flat and can support a unit placed on top for playability. It is 2 levels tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are four files. One of each building both with and without hexes so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle. Remember to print the B version if you want the extra support pegs to support units on top for playability. I advise printing these in resin if possible because they are small enough that they don't take much resin, and the details show up smoother.

As always, tipping is appreciated at: paypal.me/rainingfire416

Notable features:
-This building goes perfectly with the other military buildings I've designed.
-Detailed design including entrance door, supported walkway, and radome design.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

Always waiting to spring up on their enemy, this restaurant chain seems to spread all across the sphere. This building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support a unit placed on top for the hex locations. It is 1 level tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

The versions with text may only look good when printed in resin, so if you print with FDM you may prefer to print the NoText files. In that case, you can paint a name on the front, print off a logo to attach, or leave it blank.

Notable features:
-Building design is based on a version of the real-world equivalent restaurant. The angled entrances in particular.
-Detailed design including doors, windows, a drive through, and a detailed roof with greebles.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

A cute little Japanese restaurant for anywhere in the universe, this building is designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support a unit placed on top for all 4 hex locations. It is 1 level tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are four files. One has the building on hexes, another is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle, and there are two more versions that have the text removed from the front of the building. The versions with text may only look good when printed in resin, so if you print with FDM you may prefer to print the NoText files. In that case, you can paint a name on the front, print off a logo to attach, or leave it blank.

Notable features:
-Nice little window and door designs that evoke a Japanese feel.
-Detailed design including doors, windows, a ladder to the roof, and a detailed roof with greebles.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

-The billboard is also 2 levels tall and may support a unit if you are careful, but it is also meant as a decoration. It will require a little support to print nicely.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Some connector bitz to use drinking straws as pipes in your scratchbuild wargaming terrain.

For a long time now I avoided using drinking straws in my wargaming scenery builds because i simply didn't like the bending part. It always squished and looked arkward.
Today i came up with this rather simple but effective solution. 3D printed connectors!

The drinking straws I had had a inner diameter of 6.6mm.

If your drinking straws have a different diameter just calculate the needed scaling using the excel sheet i added or by hand [("your diameter" x 100) / 6,6]

There is a version of each connector with and without the part that goes into the drinking straw to secure it.

A library building designed to be 3D printed as terrain for 6mm tabletop gaming. The top of the building is large and flat enough to support a unit placed on top for all 23 hex locations. It is 6 levels tall if you're playing a specific mecha tabletop game.

There are two files. One has the building on hexes and the other is hexless so that you can print the one that fits your playstyle. Further, there is a second variation of this building, uploaded as â€œLibrary 1Aâ€ here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4598463

The difference between the two buildings is that 1A is the "original" version, and for 1B the faces that extend from the side of the upper part of the building do not extend as far. If you do not print at a high enough resolution then the bottom part of those faces may sag slightly on 1A. This is not an issue if you print at a high resolution, and can clean up well if you do experience sagging, but you may choose to use 1B to speed up the print time by lowering the resolution, or because your printer resolution cannot go high enough to print those extra faces without issue. 1B makes the building design less prominent, but it means that if you print the building at a low resolution then those parts won't sag at the bottom.

Notable features:
-Detailed design including doors, windows, loading docks, steps to an exterior walkway around the building, and a detailed roof area with greebles such as ducting.
-Visually interesting exterior design.
-The second floor has a curved wall supporting the larger floors on the upper part of the building. This means that the building should print without any supports, and conveniently it is also how the real life building is designed.
-This building is closely based on a real life building. It is designed as a library, but you could use it as an office building or something else if you're creative.
-This building is fairly large and would provide a great addition to your urban terrain.

The model units are in mm and it is scaled such that the hexes are 33mm from flat-to-flat, which is perfect for modern hex maps using 33mm hexes. You can always resize it if your hexes are slightly smaller/larger.

Please post pictures and leave feedback if you make this yourself! I'd love to see prints and use the feedback to adjust overhangs, detail levels, etc. on this model and future ones as well.

WIP ! WATCH THIS THING in case of updates.

This is my version of the 1995 bulkheads that were designed for Necromunda (but re-used in latter boxed sets).
They were designed to work with cardboard pieces to create platforms, catwalks and other industrial terrains.

If you are not familiar with the original, there is a video by Kiblams making the apology of this design: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DF_enN4Tz3w]

My version is designed to be printed without support with a PLA printer. It is based on Sirbats' design but with a few adjustments for better printing and new bulkhead feature design.

Without support, the printing is not perfect but tabbletop wortrhy, especially when one is trying to represent a rusty factory underworld.

Hopefully I will make more of these so keep tuned and feel free to give feedbacks !

Hello fellow printers!
================
This set of ruins is designed to be assembled in the most easy but still most versatile way. Just print a few wall sections and several copies of the pillars and the rubble. Then glue the parts together with pillars at the corners. With the rubble parts as footings you don't even need to create a base for your walls.


Printing
--------------------
- This print is designed for resin printing but don't hesitate to try it with your FDM printer and post the results!
- The full set you see on the pictures took me about 600ml of resin.
- Since I could not manage to get the parts perfectly plane on the underside you should **lower the STL file about 0.2mm below the print plate**
- No supports or rafts should be needed when these parts are printed upright in resin.


Tips for the building process
--------------------
- Use sandpaper to flatten some parts if necessary.
- Cut some single bricks from Styrofoam to add them to your bases and cover any flaws.
- Mirror your parts for more variety!
- put together two rubble parts to create a whole standalone pile
- consider putting some parts together beforehand in you slicer

- flipped vehicle
- 1 of 3 variations of head-on collisions
- 1 of 2 variations of parking meter collisions.

Pick-up truck that hit a log included!

Updated; added; tyranid_devourer_center_hollow_tendrils.stl; this has tendril feelers on all appendages; includes a slight half-sphere hollow underneath.

Update; added mirrored tower

Update; 2x new towers/chimney added; it just fits the print bed on the Afinia... barely, you'll have to rotate along the z-axis. I believe I'll have to scale the one that is completely upright, it may be possible that I'll split that file so it can be printed large enough and in multiple pieces...

Updated: image and STL file; devourer_center was printed at 85% in size.

Work-in-Progress; CCW - Dune/Alien/Tyranid Terrain (lets mashup our sci-fi genres)
Can be used as capillary towers and spore chimney

Devourer_center should be reduced/scaled based on how large you want the mandible/towers. I might end up removing the talons mashed from the Ethereal Marauder and do something different... other files to follow as they get successfully printed.

Bases print hollowed; two reasons are to reduce filament and print time; however, you could also chuck in a 6 sided dice, shake it up and set it on the table. If one of the towers/mandibles is destroyed you lift it up and see what number is revealed and that is how many termagants are generated to come and defend the objective... anyone have any Megarachnids hanging around, lol.

Working on adding more shaping/detailing/muscle, tissue and pits/boils; possibly adding a "mouth" at the top of the spires/towers. Might also be usable as a basis for Tyrannocyte/Sporocyst model...

Not sure about scale/proportions but will play around with it; I currently use Heroscape Marro Hives and old Battle For Macragge bits, so those are starting reference points for scale.

The tower design is basically repeated/scaled/modular, so it's possibly to make them larger if they are truncated so you can fit it together from large base to smaller top...
